    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-07-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-07-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="1306"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1306">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_SAE1">S/AE</gloss> Files</note>
                <head>No. 1306<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_CWS1" type="from"
                            >Churchill</persName> to the Secretary of War</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_SHL2" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stimson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <lb/>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">and personal</hi>
                    </seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary <persName corresp="#p_SHL2"
                            >Stimson</persName>
                    </hi>[:] I enclose a photostat record of the Hyde Park Agreement on T. A., for
                    which you asked the Chancellor of the Exchequer.<note n="1" xml:id="d1306fn1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_ASJ1">Sir John Anderson</persName>. Following the
                        death of President <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>, an
                        authenticated text of the enclosed <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> was
                        not available to responsible American officials. Before the Berlin
                        Conference, <persName corresp="#p_SHL2">Stimson</persName> had asked the
                        British Government to supply a photocopy of the <hi rend="italic"
                            >aide-mémoire</hi>.</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="1569" n="1371" xml:id="pg_1371"/>
                <p>This photograph was taken by a special photographic section of the Air Ministry,
                    and flown out here in the charge of a trusted officer.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CWS1">W[<hi rend="smallcaps">inston</hi>] S C[<hi
                                rend="smallcaps">hurchill</hi>]</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <closer>
                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-07-18"
                        >18.7.45</date>.</dateline>
                </closer>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Enclosure]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#left">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                        </seg>
                    </opener>
                    <p rend="center">
                        <gloss target="#t_TubeAlloys1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tube Alloys</hi>
                        </gloss>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d1306fn2">The following manuscript notation appears in
                            the top margin: “A copy of this <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> was
                            left with Pres. <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>.
                            Another copy was given to Adl. <persName corresp="#p_LFAWD1"
                                >Leahy</persName> to hand to <persName corresp="#p_CL1">Lord
                                Cherwell</persName>. J[ohn] M[iller] M[artin.]” The copy of the <hi
                                rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> in the <persName corresp="#p_RFD1"
                                >Roosevelt</persName> Papers deposited in the <persName
                                corresp="#p_RFD1">Franklin</persName> D. Rooseveit Library at Hyde
                            Park does not, of course, bear this notation nor that quoted in footnote
                            3, <hi rend="italic">infra</hi>, but it does have a handwritten date,
                            “18. 9”,i. e.,September 18, under <persName corresp="#p_CWS1"
                                >Churchill</persName>’s initials.</note>
                    </p>
                    <p rend="center">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Aide-Mémoire of Conversation Between the President and
                            the Prime Minister at Hyde Park, September</hi> 18, 1944<note n="3"
                            xml:id="d1306fn3">At this point there is the following marginal
                            manuscript notation: “actually 19th J[ohn] M[iller] M[artin.]”</note>
                    </p>
                    <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>The suggestion that the world should be informed regarding <gloss
                                target="#t_TubeAlloys1">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Tube Alloys</hi>
                            </gloss>, with a view to an international agreement regarding its
                            control and use, is not accepted. The matter should continue to be
                            regarded as of the utmost secrecy; but when a “bomb” is finally
                            available, it might perhaps, after mature consideration, be used against
                            the Japanese, who should be warned that this bombardment will be
                            repeated until they surrender.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Full collaboration between the United States and the British
                            Government in developing <gloss target="#t_TubeAlloys1">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Tube Alloys</hi>
                            </gloss> for military and commercial purposes should continue after the
                            defeat of Japan unless and until terminated by joint agreement.</item>
                    </list>
                    <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <list>
                                <item>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">F[<hi rend="smallcaps">ranklin</hi>]
                                        D R[<hi rend="smallcaps">oosevelt</hi>]</persName>
                                </item>
                                <item>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_CWS1">W[<hi rend="smallcaps">inston</hi>]
                                        S C[<hi rend="smallcaps">hurchill</hi>]</persName>
                                </item>
                            </list>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </frus:attachment>
            </div>
